🔬 Phase 2: Vulnerability Validation Report

Target: http://localhost:3000 | Generated: 2025-07-24 19:46:24

🎯 Executive Summary

This validation phase confirmed 530 security vulnerabilities through automated testing. These findings represent verified attack vectors that pose immediate risk to business operations, customer data, and regulatory compliance.

Information Items

🚨 High Risk Vulnerabilities

Missing Anti-clickjacking Header
MEDIUM
📍 URL: http://localhost/DVWA/login.php
🔧 Parameter: x-frame-options
📋 Description: The response does not protect against 'ClickJacking' attacks. It should include either Content-Security-Policy with 'frame-ancestors' directive or X-Frame-Options.
🎯 CWE ID: 1021
🔗 Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/X-Frame-Options

💼 Business Impact

Users tricked into performing unintended actions through hidden interface elements.

💰 Financial Impact: Unauthorized transactions + user account compromise

🎯 Attack Scenario

Website embedded invisibly in malicious page, users think they're clicking harmless buttons but actually perform sensitive operations.

🔍 Technical Evidence

Request: GET http://localhost/DVWA/login.php

Evidence:

Content Security Policy (CSP) Header Not Set
MEDIUM
📍 URL: http://localhost/DVWA/login.php
🔧 Parameter:
📋 Description: Content Security Policy (CSP) is an added layer of security that helps to detect and mitigate certain types of attacks, including Cross Site Scripting (XSS) and data injection attacks. These attacks are used for everything from data theft to site defacement or distribution of malware. CSP provides a set of standard HTTP headers that allow website owners to declare approved sources of content that browsers should be allowed to load on that page — covered types are JavaScript, CSS, HTML frames, fonts, images and embeddable objects such as Java applets, ActiveX, audio and video files.
🎯 CWE ID: 693
🔗 Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Security/CSP/Introducing_Content_Security_Policy https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Content_Security_Policy_Cheat_Sheet.html https://www.w3.org/TR/CSP/ https://w3c.github.io/webappsec-csp/ https://web.dev/articles/csp https://caniuse.com/#feat=contentsecuritypolicy https://content-security-policy.com/

💼 Business Impact

This vulnerability requires assessment to determine specific business impact.

💰 Financial Impact: Financial impact depends on data exposure and business disruption.

🎯 Attack Scenario

Potential security risk that could be exploited by attackers.

📋 Description: Content Security Policy (CSP) is an added layer of security that helps to detect and mitigate certain types of attacks, including Cross Site Scripting (XSS) and data injection attacks. These attacks are used for everything from data theft to site defacement or distribution of malware. CSP provides a set of standard HTTP headers that allow website owners to declare approved sources of content that browsers should be allowed to load on that page — covered types are JavaScript, CSS, HTML frames, fonts, images and embeddable objects such as Java applets, ActiveX, audio and video files.

🎯 Attack Scenario

Potential security risk that could be exploited by attackers.

🔍 Technical Evidence

Request: GET http://localhost:3000/home/kali/juice-shop/node_modules/express/lib/router/styles.css

Evidence: Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *

Content Security Policy (CSP) Header Not Set
MEDIUM
📍 URL: http://localhost:3000/home/kali/juice-shop/node_modules/express/lib/router/index.js:421:3
🔧 Parameter:
📋 Description: Content Security Policy (CSP) is an added layer of security that helps to detect and mitigate certain types of attacks, including Cross Site Scripting (XSS) and data injection attacks. These attacks are used for everything from data theft to site defacement or distribution of malware. CSP provides a set of standard HTTP headers that allow website owners to declare approved sources of content that browsers should be allowed to load on that page — covered types are JavaScript, CSS, HTML frames, fonts, images and embeddable objects such as Java applets, ActiveX, audio and video files.
🎯 CWE ID: 693

📍 URL: http://localhost:3000/home/kali/juice-shop/node_modules/serve-index/main.js
🔧 Parameter:
📋 Description: Content Security Policy (CSP) is an added layer of security that helps to detect and mitigate certain types of attacks, including Cross Site Scripting (XSS) and data injection attacks. These attacks are used for everything from data theft to site defacement or distribution of malware. CSP provides a set of standard HTTP headers that allow website owners to declare approved sources of content that browsers should be allowed to load on that page — covered types are JavaScript, CSS, HTML frames, fonts, images and embeddable objects such as Java applets, ActiveX, audio and video files.
🎯 CWE ID: 693
🔗 Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Security/CSP/Introducing_Content_Security_Policy https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Content_Security_Policy_Cheat_Sheet.html https://www.w3.org/TR/CSP/ https://w3c.github.io/webappsec-csp/ https://web.dev/articles/csp https://caniuse.com/#feat=contentsecuritypolicy https://content-security-policy.com/

Request: GET http://localhost/DVWA/login.php

Evidence: Apache/2.4.64 (Debian)

X-Content-Type-Options Header Missing
LOW
📍 URL: http://localhost/DVWA/login.php
🔧 Parameter: x-content-type-options
📋 Description: The Anti-MIME-Sniffing header X-Content-Type-Options was not set to 'nosniff'. This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.
🎯 CWE ID: 693
🔗 Reference: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/internet-explorer/ie-developer/compatibility/gg622941(v=vs.85) https://owasp.org/www-community/Security_Headers

This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.
🎯 CWE ID: 693
🔗 Reference: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/internet-explorer/ie-developer/compatibility/gg622941(v=vs.85) https://owasp.org/www-community/Security_Headers

💼 Business Impact

This vulnerability requires assessment to determine specific business impact.

💰 Financial Impact: Financial impact depends on data exposure and business disruption.

🎯 Attack Scenario

Potential security risk that could be exploited by attackers.

🔍 Technical Evidence

Request: GET http://localhost/DVWA/dvwa/images/login_logo.png

Evidence:

Cookie without SameSite Attribute
LOW
📍 URL: http://localhost/DVWA/vulnerabilities/xss_s/
🔧 Parameter: security
📋 Description: A cookie has been set without the SameSite attribute, which means that the cookie can be sent as a result of a 'cross-site' request. The SameSite attribute is an effective counter measure to cross-site request forgery, cross-site script inclusion, and timing attacks.
🎯 CWE ID: 1275
🔗 Reference: https://tools.ietf.org/html/draft-ietf-httpbis-cookie-same-site

🚨 Informational Findings

Session Management Response Identified
INFORMATIONAL
📍 URL: http://localhost/DVWA/vulnerabilities/sqli_blind/
🔧 Parameter: security
📋 Description: The given response has been identified as containing a session management token. The 'Other Info' field contains a set of header tokens that can be used in the Header Based Session Management Method. If the request is in a context which has a Session Management Method set to "Auto-Detect" then this rule will change the session management to use the tokens identified.
🎯 CWE ID: -1
🔗 Reference: https://www.zaproxy.org/docs/desktop/addons/authentication-helper/session-mgmt-id

💼 Business Impact

This vulnerability requires assessment to determine specific business impact.

💰 Financial Impact: Financial impact depends on data exposure and business disruption.

🎯 Attack Scenario

Potential security risk that could be exploited by attackers.

🔍 Technical Evidence

Request: GET http://localhost/DVWA/vulnerabilities/sqli_blind/

Evidence: security

Session Management Response Identified
INFORMATIONAL
📍 URL: http://localhost/DVWA/vulnerabilities/sqli_blind/
🔧 Parameter: security
📋 Description: The given response has been identified as containing a session management token. The 'Other Info' field contains a set of header tokens that can be used in the Header Based Session Management Method. If the request is in a context which has a Session Management Method set to "Auto-Detect" then this rule will change the session management to use the tokens identified.
🎯 CWE ID: -1
🔗 Reference: https://www.zaproxy.org/docs/desktop/addons/authentication-helper/session-mgmt-id

💼 Business Impact

This vulnerability requires assessment to determine specific business impact.

💰 Financial Impact: Financial impact depends on data exposure and business disruption.

🎯 Attack Scenario

Potential security risk that could be exploited by attackers.

🔍 Technical Evidence

Request: GET http://localhost/DVWA/vulnerabilities/sqli_blind/

Evidence: security

Authentication Request Identified
INFORMATIONAL
📍 URL: http://localhost/DVWA/login.php
🔧 Parameter: Login
📋 Description: The given request has been identified as an authentication request. The 'Other Info' field contains a set of key=value lines which identify any relevant fields. If the request is in a context which has an Authentication Method set to "Auto-Detect" then this rule will change the authentication to match the request identified.
🎯 CWE ID: -1
🔗 Reference: https://www.zaproxy.org/docs/desktop/addons/authentication-helper/auth-req-id/

💼 Business Impact

This vulnerability requires assessment to determine specific business impact.

💰 Financial Impact: Financial impact depends on data exposure and business disruption.

🎯 Attack Scenario

Potential security risk that could be exploited by attackers.

🔍 Technical Evidence

Request: POST http://localhost/DVWA/login.php

Evidence: password

Session Management Response Identified
INFORMATIONAL
📍 URL: http://localhost/DVWA/login.php
🔧 Parameter: PHPSESSID
📋 Description: The given response has been identified as containing a session management token. The 'Other Info' field contains a set of header tokens that can be used in the Header Based Session Management Method. If the request is in a context which has a Session Management Method set to "Auto-Detect" then this rule will change the session management to use the tokens identified.
🎯 CWE ID: -1
🔗 Reference: https://www.zaproxy.org/docs/desktop/addons/authentication-helper/session-mgmt-id

💼 Business Impact

This vulnerability requires assessment to determine specific business impact.

💰 Financial Impact: Financial impact depends on data exposure and business disruption.

🎯 Attack Scenario

Potential security risk that could be exploited by attackers.

🔍 Technical Evidence

Request: POST http://localhost/DVWA/login.php

Evidence: PHPSESSID

User Agent Fuzzer
INFORMATIONAL
📍 URL: http://localhost/DVWA/login.php
🔧 Parameter: Header User-Agent
📋 Description: Check for differences in response based on fuzzed User Agent (eg. mobile sites, access as a Search Engine Crawler). Compares the response statuscode and the hashcode of the response body with the original response.
🎯 CWE ID: 0
🔗 Reference: https://owasp.org/wstg

📍 URL: http://localhost/DVWA/vulnerabilities/xss_s
🔧 Parameter: Header User-Agent
📋 Description: Check for differences in response based on fuzzed User Agent (eg. mobile sites, access as a Search Engine Crawler). Compares the response statuscode and the hashcode of the response body with the original response.
🎯 CWE ID: 0
🔗 Reference: https://owasp.org/wstg
